# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dns-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] An alternative to DoH is the DNS over TLS (DoT) protocol, a similar standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Based on privacy and security, whether either protocol is superior is a matter of debate, while others argue that the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DoH is a proposed standard, published as RFC 8484 (October 2018) by the IETF.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] It uses HTTPS, and supports the *wire format* DNS response data, as returned in existing UDP responses, in an HTTPS payload with the MIME type *application/dns-message*.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] The underlying HTTP layer can be any version of HTTP, though HTTP/2 is the *recommended* minimum.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] If HTTP/2 is used, the server may also use HTTP/2 server push to send values that it anticipates the client may find useful in advance.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Even though the IETF has published RFC 8484 as a proposed standard and companies are experimenting with it, the IETF has yet to determine how it should best be implemented.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] The IETF is evaluating a number of approaches for how best to deploy DoH and has established a working group, Adaptive DNS Discovery (ADD), to do this work and develop a consensus.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Since DoH cannot be used under some circumstances, like captive portals, web browsers like Firefox can be configured to fall back to insecure DNS.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] The de facto DoH URL is *https://host_name/dns-query*.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Oblivious DNS over HTTPS (ODoH) is an experimental standard, published as RFC 9230 (June 2022) by the IETF, proposing a protocol extension to ensure no single DoH server is aware of both the client's IP address and the content of their DNS queries and responses.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] This is an application of a security principle called decoupling or privacy partitioning.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] A different protocol with the same name (Oblivious DoH) was originally developed as Oblivious DNS (ODNS) by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH itself was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In ODoH and ODNS, all DNS requests and responses are routed via a proxy, hiding the client's address from the resolver.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Requests and responses are encrypted to hide their contents from the proxy, and only the resolver can decrypt the requests, and the client the responses.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Thus, the proxy knows the client address and resolver but not the request, and the resolver knows the proxy and request but not the client address, preventing the client address being linked to the query, unless both the proxy and resolver servers collude.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Another protocol, Oblivious HTTP, uses similar architectural principles for HTTP requests.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DoH is used for recursive DNS resolution by DNS resolvers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Resolvers (*DoH clients*) must have access to a DoH server hosting a query endpoint.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Apple's iOS 14 and macOS 11 released in late 2020 support both DoH and DoT protocols.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In iOS, the protocols can be used via configuration profiles.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In November 2019, Microsoft announced plans to implement support for encrypted DNS protocols in Microsoft Windows, beginning with DoH.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In May 2020, Microsoft released Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 19628 that included initial support for DoH along with instructions on how to enable it via registry and command line interface.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 20185 added a graphical user interface for specifying a DoH resolver.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DoH support is not included in Windows 10 21H2.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Android 11 onwards supports DNS over HTTP/3 (DoH3) if a July 2022 system update is installed.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] BIND 9, an open source DNS resolver from Internet Systems Consortium added native support for DoH in version 9.17.10.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DNSdist, an open source DNS proxy/load balancer from PowerDNS, added native support for DoH in version 1.4.0 in April 2019.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Unbound, an open source DNS resolver created by NLnet Labs, has supported DoH since version 1.12.0, released in October 2020.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] It first implemented support for DNS encryption using the alternative DoT protocol much earlier, starting with version 1.4.14, released in December 2011.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Unbound runs on most operating systems, including distributions of Linux, BSD, MacOS, and Windows.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS is available in Google Chrome 83 or later for Windows, Linux, and macOS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Chrome will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] It is also possible to manually specify a preset or custom DoH server to use within the user interface.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In September 2020, Google Chrome for Android began staged rollout of DNS over HTTPS.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Users can configure a custom resolver or disable DNS over HTTPS in settings.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Google Chrome has five DNS-over-HTTPS providers pre-configured, which are Google Public DNS, Cloudflare's 1.1.1.1, Quad9's 9.9.9.9, NextDNS, and CleanBrowsing.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Microsoft Edge supports DNS over HTTPS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Edge will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In 2018, Mozilla partnered with Cloudflare to deliver DoH for Firefox users that enable it (known as Trusted Recursive Resolver).
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] On February 25, 2020, Firefox started enabling DNS over HTTPS for all US-based users, relying on Cloudflare's resolver by default.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Opera supports DoH, configurable via the browser settings page.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] By default, DNS queries are sent to Cloudflare servers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Brave implemented DNS over HTTPS (DoH) by default for its desktop browser in version 1.4, released in April 2020, as part of its broader privacy-focused features to encrypt DNS queries and prevent third-party eavesdropping or manipulation.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS server implementations are already available free of charge by some public DNS providers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DoH can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes; the 2019 DDoS worm Godlua used DoH to mask connections to its command-and-control server.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In January 2021, NSA warned enterprises against using external DoH resolvers because they prevent DNS query filtering, inspection, and audit.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Instead, NSA recommends configuring enterprise-owned DoH resolvers and blocking all known external DoH resolvers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] DoH has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for DoH by operating DoH servers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In response to the criticism, the ISPA apologized and withdrew the nomination.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] Mozilla subsequently stated that DoH will not be used by default in the British market until further discussion with relevant stakeholders, but stated that it "would offer real security benefits to UK citizens".
[src:dns-security/dns-over-https] In July 2020, iYouPort, the University of Maryland, and the Great Firewall Report, reported that the Great Firewall (GFW) by the Chinese government blocks TLS connections using the encrypted SNI extension in China.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] While DNS over TLS is applicable to any DNS transaction, it was first standardized for use between stub or forwarding resolvers and recursive resolvers, in RFC 7858 in May of 2016.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Subsequent IETF efforts specify the use of DoT between recursive and authoritative servers ("Authoritative DNS over TLS" or "ADoT") and a related implementation between authoritative servers (Zone Transfer-over-TLS or "xfr-over-TLS").
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] BIND supports DoT connections as of version 9.17.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Earlier versions offered DoT capability by proxying through stunnel.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Unbound has supported DNS over TLS since 22 January 2023.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Unwind has supported DoT since 29 January 2023.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] With Android Pie's support for DNS over TLS, some ad blockers now support using the encrypted protocol as a relatively easy way to access their services versus any of the various work-around methods typically used such as VPNs and proxy servers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Android clients running Android Pie or newer support DNS over TLS and will use it by default if the network infrastructure, for example the ISP, supports it.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] In April 2018, Google announced that Android Pie will include support for DNS over TLS, allowing users to set a DNS server phone-wide on both Wi-Fi and mobile connections, an option that was historically only possible on rooted devices or by using VPNService API.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DNSDist, from PowerDNS, also announced support for DNS over TLS in version 1.3.0.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Linux and Windows users can use DNS over TLS as a client through the NLnet Labs stubby daemon or Knot Resolver.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Alternatively they may install getdns-utils to use DoT directly with the getdns_query tool.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] The unbound DNS resolver by NLnet Labs also supports DNS over TLS.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Apple's iOS 14 introduced OS-level support for DNS over TLS (and DNS over HTTPS). iOS does not allow manual configuration of DoT servers, and requires the use of a third-party application to make configuration changes.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] systemd-resolved is a Linux-only implementation that can be configured to use DNS over TLS, by editing `/etc/systemd/resolved.conf` and enabling the setting `DNSOverTLS`.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Most major Linux distributions have systemd installed by default.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DNS over TLS was first implemented in a public recursive resolver by Quad9 in 2017.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Other recursive resolver operators such as Google and Cloudflare followed suit in subsequent years, and now it is a broadly-supported feature generally available in most large recursive resolvers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DoT can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DoT has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for both DoT and DoH.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] In that scenario, DNS queries are checked against block lists once they are received by the provider rather than prior to leaving the user's router.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] As with any communication, encryption of DNS requests by itself does not protect privacy.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] It protects against third-party observers, but does not guarantee what the endpoints do with the (then decrypted) data.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DoT clients do not necessarily directly query any authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] The client may rely on the DoT server using traditional (port 53 or 853) queries to finally reach authoritative servers.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] Thus, DoT does not qualify as an end-to-end encrypted protocol, only hop-to-hop encrypted and only if DNS over TLS is used consistently.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DNS over HTTPS (DoH) is a similar protocol standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery from DoT.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] On the basis of privacy and security, whether or not a superior protocol exists among the two is a matter of controversial debate, while others argue the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-security/dns-over-tls] DNSCrypt is another network protocol that authenticates and encrypts DNS traffic, although it was never proposed to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) with a Request for Comments (RFC).
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] A Domain Name System server translates a human-readable domain name (such as `example.com`) into a numerical IP address that is used to route communications between nodes.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Normally if the server does not know a requested translation it will ask another server, and the process continues recursively.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] To increase performance, a server will typically remember (cache) these translations for a certain amount of time.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] This means if it receives another request for the same translation, it can reply without needing to ask any other servers, until that cache expires.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] When a DNS server has received a false translation and caches it for performance optimization, it is considered *poisoned*, and it supplies the false data to clients.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] If a DNS server is poisoned, it may return an incorrect IP address, diverting traffic to another computer (often an attacker's).
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Normally, a networked computer uses a DNS server provided by an Internet service provider (ISP) or the computer user's organization.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] DNS servers are used in an organization's network to improve resolution response performance by caching previously obtained query results.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Poisoning attacks on a single DNS server can affect the users serviced directly by the compromised server or those serviced indirectly by its downstream server(s) if applicable.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] To perform a cache poisoning attack, the attacker exploits flaws in the DNS software.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] A server should correctly validate DNS responses to ensure that they are from an authoritative source (for example by using DNSSEC); otherwise the server might end up caching the incorrect entries locally and serve them to other users that make the same request.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] This attack can be used to redirect users from a website to another site of the attacker's choosing.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] For example, an attacker spoofs the IP address DNS entries for a target website on a given DNS server and replaces them with the IP address of a server under their control.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] The attacker then creates files on the server under their control with names matching those on the target server.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] These files usually contain malicious content, such as computer worms or viruses.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] A user whose computer has referenced the poisoned DNS server gets tricked into accepting content coming from a non-authentic server and unknowingly downloads the malicious content.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] This technique can also be used for phishing attacks, where a fake version of a genuine website is created to gather personal details such as bank and credit/debit card details.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] The vulnerability of systems to DNS cache poisoning goes beyond its immediate effects as it can open users up to further risks such as phishing, malware injections, denial of service, and website hijacking due to system vulnerabilities.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Various methods, ranging from the use of social engineering tactics to the exploitation of weaknesses present in the DNS server software, can lead to these attacks.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] In the following variants, the entries for the server ns.target.example would be poisoned and redirected to the attacker's name server at IP address *w.x.y.z*.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] These attacks assume that the name server for target.example is ns.target.example.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] To accomplish the attacks, the attacker must force the target DNS server to make a request for a domain controlled by one of the attacker's nameservers.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] The first variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the name server of the attacker's domain to the name server of the target domain, then assigning that name server an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] DNS server's request: what are the address records for subdomain.attacker.example?
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the additional A-record (IP address) for ns.target.example, allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] The second variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the nameserver of another domain unrelated to the original request to an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the unrelated authority information for target.example's NS-record (nameserver entry), allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Many cache poisoning attacks against DNS servers can be prevented by being less trusting of the information passed to them by other DNS servers, and ignoring any DNS records passed back that are not directly relevant to the query.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] For example, versions of BIND 9.5.0-P1 and above perform these checks.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Source port randomization for DNS requests, combined with the use of cryptographically secure random numbers for selecting both the source port and the 16-bit cryptographic nonce, can greatly reduce the probability of successful DNS race attacks.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] However, when routers, firewalls, proxies, and other gateway devices perform network address translation (NAT), or more specifically, port address translation (PAT), they may rewrite source ports in order to track connection state.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] When modifying source ports, PAT devices may remove source port randomness implemented by nameservers and stub resolvers.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Secure DNS (DNSSEC) uses cryptographic digital signatures signed with a trusted public key certificate to determine the authenticity of data.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] DNSSEC can counter cache poisoning attacks.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] In 2010 DNSSEC was implemented in the Internet root zone servers, but needs to be deployed on all top level domain servers as well.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] The DNSSEC readiness of these is shown in the list of Internet top-level domains.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] As of 2020, all of the original TLDs support DNSSEC, as do country code TLDs of most large countries, but many country-code TLDs still do not.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Many second-level domains also do not support DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] This kind of attack can be mitigated at the transport layer or application layer by performing end-to-end validation once a connection is established.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] A common example of this is the use of Transport Layer Security and digital signatures.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] For example, by using HTTPS (the secure version of HTTP), users may check whether the server's digital certificate is valid and belongs to a website's expected owner.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] Similarly, the secure shell remote login program checks digital certificates at endpoints (if known) before proceeding with the session.
[src:dns-security/dns-spoofing] For applications that download updates automatically, the application can embed a copy of the signing certificate locally and validate the signature stored in the software update against the embedded certificate.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The **Domain Name System Security Extensions** (**DNSSEC**) is a suite of extension specifications by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for securing data exchanged in the Domain Name System (DNS) in Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The protocol provides cryptographic authentication of data, authenticated denial of existence, and data integrity, but not availability or confidentiality.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 2025, DNSSEC deployment is spotty.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The original design of the Domain Name System did not include any security features.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It was conceived only as a scalable distributed system.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) attempt to add security, while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] RFC 3833 of 2004 documents some of the known threats to the DNS, and their solutions in DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was designed to protect applications using DNS from accepting forged or manipulated DNS data, such as that created by DNS cache poisoning.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] All answers from DNSSEC protected zones are digitally signed.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By checking the digital signature, a DNS resolver is able to check if the information is identical (i.e. unmodified and complete) to the information published by the zone owner and served on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC *does not* provide confidentiality of data; in particular, all DNSSEC responses are authenticated but not encrypted.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC *does not* protect against DoS attacks directly, though it indirectly provides some benefit (because signature checking allows the use of potentially untrustworthy parties).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Other standards (not DNSSEC) are used to secure bulk data (such as a DNS zone transfer) sent between DNS servers.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As documented in RFC 4367, some users and developers make false assumptions about DNS names, such as assuming that a company's common name plus ".com" is always its domain name.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC cannot protect against false assumptions; it can only authenticate that the data is truly from or not available from the domain owner.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DNSSEC specifications (called *DNSSEC-bis*) describe the current DNSSEC protocol in great detail.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] With the publication of these new RFCs (March 2005), an earlier RFC, RFC 2535 has become obsolete.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The full set of RFCs that specify DNSSEC are collected in RFC 9364, which is also BCP 237.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of March 2026, DNSSEC is only operational in 83 (45%) of country code top-level domains.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ICANN made DNSSEC mandatory for new generic top-level domains in 2014.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Verisign reported about 5% adoption in .net second-level domains and about 4% in .com.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Second-level domain adoption exceeds 50% in .nl (Netherlands), .cz (Czech Republic), .no (Norway), .se (Sweden), and .nu (Niue, but used to sound like "new").
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 2023, major domains like google.com, amazon.com, and microsoft.com were unsigned.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC works by digitally signing records for DNS lookup using public-key cryptography.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The correct DNSKEY record is authenticated via a chain of trust, starting with a set of verified public keys for the DNS root zone which is the trusted third party.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Domain owners generate their own keys, and upload them using their DNS control panel at their domain-name registrar, which in turn pushes the keys via secDNS to the zone operator (e.g., Verisign for .com) who signs and publishes them in DNS.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS is implemented by the use of several resource records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains the DNSSEC signature for a record set.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS resolvers verify the signature with a public key, stored in a DNSKEY record.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains the public key that a DNS resolver uses to verify DNSSEC signatures in RRSIG records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] References a DNSKEY record in the sub-delegated zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS record is placed in the parent zone along with the delegating NS records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains a link to the next record name in the zone and lists the record types that exist for the record's name.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS resolvers use NSEC records to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Contains links to the next record name in the zone (in hashed name sorting order) and lists the record types that exist for the name covered by the hash value in the first label of the NSEC3 record's own name.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These records can be used by resolvers to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC3 records are similar to NSEC records, but NSEC3 uses cryptographically hashed record names to avoid the enumeration of the record names in a zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Authoritative DNS servers use this record to calculate and determine which NSEC3 records to include in responses to DNSSEC requests for non-existing names/types.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When DNSSEC is used, each answer to a DNS lookup contains an RRSIG DNS record, in addition to the record type that was requested.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The RRSIG record is a digital signature of the answer DNS resource record set.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The digital signature is verified by locating the correct public key found in a DNSKEY record.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC and NSEC3 records are used to provide cryptographic evidence of the non-existence of any Resource Record (RR).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS record is used in the authentication of DNSKEYs in the lookup procedure using the chain of trust.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC and NSEC3 records are used for robust resistance against spoofing.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was designed to be extensible so that as attacks are discovered against existing algorithms, new ones can be introduced in a backward-compatible fashion as described in RFC 8624.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] From the results of a DNS lookup, a security-aware DNS resolver can determine whether the authoritative name server for the domain being queried supports DNSSEC, whether the answer it receives is secure, and whether there is some sort of error.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The lookup procedure is different for recursive name servers such as those of many ISPs, and for stub resolvers such as those included by default in mainstream operating systems.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Microsoft Windows uses a stub resolver, and Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7 in particular use a non-validating but DNSSEC-aware stub resolver.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Using the chain of trust model, a Delegation Signer (DS) record in a parent domain (DNS zone) can be used to verify a DNSKEY record in a subdomain, which can then contain other DS records to verify further subdomains.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Say that a recursive resolver such as an ISP name server wants to get the IP addresses (A record and/or AAAA records) of the domain "www.example.com".
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When the resolver receives an answer via the normal DNS lookup process, it then checks to make sure that the answer is correct.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Ideally, the security-aware resolver would start with verifying the DS and DNSKEY records at the DNS root.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Then it would use the DS records for the "com" top-level domain found at the root to verify the DNSKEY records in the "com" zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] From there, it would see if there is a DS record for the "example.com" subdomain in the "com" zone, and if there were, it would then use the DS record to verify a DNSKEY record found in the "example.com" zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, it would verify the RRSIG record found in the answer for the A records for "www.example.com".
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] There are several exceptions to the above example.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] First, if "example.com" does not support DNSSEC, there will be no RRSIG record in the answer and there will not be a DS record for "example.com" in the "com" zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] If there is a DS record for "example.com", but no RRSIG record in the reply, something is wrong and maybe a man in the middle attack is going on, stripping the DNSSEC information and modifying the A records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Or, it could be a broken security-oblivious name server along the way that stripped the DO flag bit from the query or the RRSIG record from the answer.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Next, it may be that there is not a domain name named "www.example.com", in which case instead of returning a RRSIG record in the answer, there will be either an NSEC record or an NSEC3 record.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These are "next secure" records that allow the resolver to prove that a domain name does not exist.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC/NSEC3 records have RRSIG records, which can be verified as above.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, it may be that the "example.com" zone implements DNSSEC, but either the "com" zone or the root zone do not, creating an "island of security" which needs to be validated in some other way.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of 15 July 2010, deployment of DNSSEC to root is completed.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The .com domain was signed with valid security keys and the secure delegation was added to the root zone on 1 April 2011.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A *validating stub resolver* can also potentially perform its own signature validation by setting the Checking Disabled (CD) bit in its query messages.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A validating stub resolver uses the CD bit to perform its own recursive authentication.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Using such a validating stub resolver gives the client end-to-end DNS security for domains implementing DNSSEC, even if the Internet service provider or the connection to them is not trusted.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Non-validating stub resolvers must rely on external DNSSEC validation services, such as those controlled by the user's Internet service provider or a public recursive name server, and the communication channels between itself and those name servers, using methods such as DNS over TLS.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To be able to prove that a DNS answer is correct, one needs to know at least one key or DS record that is correct from sources other than the DNS.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These starting points are known as **trust anchors** and are typically obtained with the operating system or via some other trusted source.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When DNSSEC was originally designed, it was thought that the only trust anchor that would be needed was for the DNS root.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The root anchors were first published on 15 July 2010.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] An *authentication chain* is a series of linked DS and DNSKEY records, starting with a trust anchor to the authoritative name server for the domain in question.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Without a complete authentication chain, an answer to a DNS lookup cannot be securely authenticated.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To limit replay attacks, there are not only the normal DNS TTL values for caching purposes, but additional timestamps in RRSIG records to limit the validity of a signature.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unlike TTL values which are relative to when the records were sent, the timestamps are absolute.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means that all security-aware DNS resolvers must have clocks that are fairly closely in sync, say to within a few minutes.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] These timestamps imply that a zone must regularly be re-signed and re-distributed to secondary servers, or the signatures will be rejected by validating resolvers.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC involves many different keys, stored both in DNSKEY records, and from other sources to form trust anchors.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In order to allow for replacement keys, a **key rollover** scheme is required.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Typically, this involves first rolling out new keys in new DNSKEY records, in addition to the existing old keys.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Then, when it is safe to assume that the time to live values have caused the caching of old keys to have passed, these new keys can be used.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Finally, when it is safe to assume that the caching of records using the old keys have expired, the old DNSKEY records can be deleted.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This process is more complicated for things such as the keys to trust anchors, such as at the root, which may require an update of the operating system.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Keys in DNSKEY records can be used for two different things and typically different DNSKEY records are used for each.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] First, there are **key signing keys** (KSK) which are used to sign other DNSKEY records containing **zone signing keys** (ZSK), which are used to sign other records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Since the ZSKs are under complete control and use by one particular DNS zone, they can be switched more easily and more often.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As a result, ZSKs can be much shorter than KSKs and still offer the same level of protection while reducing the size of the RRSIG/DNSKEY records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When a new KSK is created, the DS record must be transferred to the parent zone and published there.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DS records use a message digest of the KSK instead of the complete key in order to keep the size of the records small.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is helpful for zones such as the .com domain, which are very large.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The procedure to update DS keys in the parent zone is also simpler than earlier DNSSEC versions that required DNSKEY records to be in the parent zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A closely related principle is that of **Algorithm rollover**, this involves migrating a zone from one signing Algorithm to another.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A good example of this would be migrating from Algorithm 8 (RSA/SHA-256) to Algorithm 13 (ECDSA/SHA-256).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Several ccTLD's have already migrated including .at, .br, .cz, .ch, .fr, .ie, .nl and .ph.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Verisign migrated .com, .net and .edu to Algorithm 13 in late 2023.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The migration of the root domain from Algorithm 8 to Algorithm 13 is currently in planning as of early 2024.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) is an IETF working group with the goal of developing protocols and techniques that allow Internet applications to establish cryptographically secured communications with TLS, DTLS, SMTP, and S/MIME based on DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The new protocols will enable additional assurances and constraints for the traditional model based on public key infrastructure.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] They will also enable domain holders to assert certificates for themselves, without reference to third-party certificate authorities.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Support for DNSSEC stapled certificates was enabled in Google Chrome 14, but was later removed.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For Mozilla Firefox, support was provided by an add-on up to Firefox 56, while native support was proposed but ultimately rejected.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS is a critical and fundamental Internet service, yet in 1990 Steve Bellovin discovered serious security flaws in it.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Research into securing it began, and progressed dramatically when his paper was made public in 1995.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The initial RFC 2065 was published by the IETF in 1997, and initial attempts to implement that specification led to a revised (and believed fully workable) specification in 1999 as IETF RFC 2535.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Plans were made to deploy DNSSEC based on RFC 2535.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unfortunately, the IETF RFC 2535 specification had very significant problems scaling up to the full Internet; by 2001 it became clear that this specification was unusable for large networks.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In normal operation DNS servers often get out of sync with their parents.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This isn't usually a problem, but when DNSSEC is enabled, this out-of-sync data could have the effect of a serious self-created denial of service.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Also, public key changes could have absurd effects; for example, if the ".com" zone changed its public key, it would have to send 22 million records (because it would need to update all of the signatures in all of its children).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus, DNSSEC as defined in RFC 2535 could not scale up to the Internet.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The IETF fundamentally modified DNSSEC, which is called *DNSSEC-bis* when necessary to distinguish it from the original DNSSEC approach of RFC 2535.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This new version uses "delegation signer (DS) resource records" to provide an additional level of indirection at delegation points between a parent and child zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In the new approach, when a child's master public key changes, instead of having six messages for every record in the child, there is one simple message: the child sends the new public key to its parent (signed, of course).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Parents simply store one master public key for each child; this is much more practical.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means that a little data is pushed to the parent, instead of massive amounts of data being exchanged between the parent and children.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This does mean that clients have to do a little more work when verifying keys.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] More specifically, verifying a DNS zone's KEY RRset requires two signature verification operations instead of the one required by RFC 2535 (there is no impact on the number of signatures verified for other types of RRsets).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Most view this as a small price to pay, since it makes DNSSEC deployment more practical.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The new version is published in RFC4033-4035.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In January 2024, a "KeyTrap" denial-of-service attack was announced for all specification-respecting DNSSEC resolvers.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DNSSEC specification (RFC4033-4035) specifies that a resolver, when receiving a signed packet from the upstream, should try *all* keys with the correct "tag" on *all* signatures until one of the combinations successfully verifies.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By putting many keys with the same "tag" and many signatures corresponding to that "tag" in a packet, the researchers can slow down a resolver by a factor of 2 million.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In response, resolvers began to place limits on the amount of verification errors, key tag collisions, and hash calculations.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Cryptographically proving the absence of a domain requires signing the response to every query for a non-existent domain.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is not a problem for online signing servers, which keep their keys available online.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, DNSSEC was designed around using offline computers to sign records so that zone-signing-keys could be kept in cold storage.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This represents a problem when trying to authenticate responses to queries for non-existent domains since it is impossible to pre-generate a response to every possible hostname query.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The initial solution was to create NSEC records for every pair of domains in a zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus if a client queried for a record at the non-existent `k.example.com`, the server would respond with an NSEC record stating that nothing exists between `a.example.com` and `z.example.com`.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, this leaks more information about the zone than traditional unauthenticated NXDOMAIN errors because it exposes the existence of real domains.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The NSEC3 records (RFC 5155) were created as an alternative which hashes the name instead of listing them directly.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Over time, advancements in hashing using GPUs and dedicated hardware meant that NSEC3 responses could be cheaply brute forced using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NSEC5 has been proposed to allow authoritative servers to sign NSEC responses without having to keep a private key that can be used to modify the zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus stealing an NSEC5KEY would only result in the ability to more easily enumerate a zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Due to the messy evolution of the protocol and a desire to preserve backwards compatibility, online DNSSEC signing servers return a "white lie" instead of authenticating a denial of existence directly.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The technique outlined in RFC 4470 returns a NSEC record in which the pairs of domains lexically surround the requested domain.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For example, request for `k.example.com` would thus result in an NSEC record proving that nothing exists between the (fictitious) domains `j.example.com` and `l.example.com`.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is also possible with NSEC3 records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Cloudflare pioneered a pair of alternative approaches, which manage to achieve the same result in one third of the response size.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The first is a variation on the "white lies" approach, called "black lies", which exploits common DNS client behavior to state the nonexistence more compactly.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The second approach instead chooses to prove that "the record exists but the requested record type does not", which they call "DNS shotgun".
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Internet is critical infrastructure, yet its operation depends on the fundamentally insecure DNS.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Thus, there is strong incentive to secure DNS, and deploying DNSSEC is generally considered to be a critical part of that effort.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] *National Strategy to Secure Cyberspace* specifically identified the need to secure DNS.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Wide-scale deployment of DNSSEC could resolve many other security problems as well, such as secure key distribution for e-mail addresses.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC deployment in large-scale networks is also challenging.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC can be deployed at any level of a DNS hierarchy, but it must be widely available in a zone before many others will want to adopt it.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNS servers must be updated with software that supports DNSSEC, and DNSSEC data must be created and added to the DNS zone data.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] A TCP/IP-using client must have their DNS resolver (client) updated before it can use DNSSEC's capabilities.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] What is more, any resolver must have, or have a way to acquire, at least one public key that it can trust before it can start using DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC implementation can add significant load to some DNS servers.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Common DNSSEC-signed responses are far larger than the default UDP size of 512 bytes.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In theory, this can be handled through multiple IP fragments, but many "middleboxes" in the field do not handle these correctly.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Yet many current TCP implementations store a great deal of data for each TCP connection; heavily loaded servers can run out of resources simply trying to respond to a larger number of (possibly bogus) DNSSEC requests.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Some protocol extensions, such as TCP Cookie Transactions, have been developed to reduce this loading.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To address these challenges, significant effort is ongoing to deploy DNSSEC, because the Internet is so vital to so many organizations.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ARIN is also signing their reverse zones.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In February 2007, TDC became the first Swedish ISP to start offering this feature to its customers.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] IANA publicly tested a sample signed root since June 2007.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] During this period prior to the production signing of the root, there were also several alternative trust anchors.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The IKS Jena introduced one on January 19, 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced another on March 27 of the same year, while ICANN themselves announced a third on February 17, 2009.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 2, 2009, Afilias, the registry service provider for Public Interest Registry's .org zone signed the .org TLD.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Afilias and PIR also detailed on September 26, 2008, that the first phase, involving large registrars it has a strong working relationship with ("friends and family") would be the first to be able to sign their domains, beginning "early 2009".
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 23, 2010, 13 registrars were listed as offering DNSSEC records for .ORG domains.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] VeriSign ran a pilot project to allow .com and .net domains to register themselves for the purpose of NSEC3 experimentation.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This goal was achieved on-schedule and Verisign's DNSSEC VP, Matt Larson, won InfoWorld's Technology Leadership Award for 2011 for his role in advancing DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC was first deployed at the root level on July 15, 2010.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This is expected to greatly simplify the deployment of DNSSEC resolvers, since the root trust anchor can be used to validate any DNSSEC zone that has a complete chain of trust from the root.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Since the chain of trust must be traced back to a trusted root without interruption in order to validate, trust anchors must still be configured for secure zones if any of the zones above them are not secure.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] For example, if the zone "signed.example.org" was secured but the "example.org" zone was not, then, even though the ".org" zone and the root are signed, a trust anchor has to be deployed in order to validate the zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2008, ICANN and VeriSign each published implementation proposals and in October, the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) asked the public for comments.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It is unclear if the comments received affected the design of the final deployment plan.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On June 3, 2009, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) announced plans to sign the root by the end of 2009, in conjunction with ICANN, VeriSign and the NTIA.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On October 6, 2009, at the 59th RIPE Conference meeting, ICANN and VeriSign announced the planned deployment timeline for deploying DNSSEC within the root zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] At the meeting it was announced that it would be incrementally deployed to one root name server a month, starting on December 1, 2009, with the final root name server serving a DNSSEC signed zone on July 1, 2010, and the root zone will be signed with a RSA/SHA256 DNSKEY.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] During the incremental roll-out period the root zone will serve a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ) that uses dummy keys, with the final DNSKEY record not being distributed until July 1, 2010.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This means the keys that were used to sign the zone use are deliberately unverifiable; the reason for this deployment was to monitor changes in traffic patterns caused by the larger responses to queries requesting DNSSEC resource records.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The .org top-level domain was signed with DNSSEC in June 2010, followed by .com, .net, and .edu later in 2010 and 2011.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Country code top-level domains were able to deposit keys starting in May 2010.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of November 2011 more than 25% of top-level domains are signed with DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On January 25, 2010, the L (ell) root server began serving a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ).
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The zone uses signatures of a SHA-2 (SHA-256) hash created using the RSA algorithm, as defined in RFC 5702.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] As of May 2010, all thirteen root servers began serving the DURZ.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On July 15, 2010, the first root full production DNSSEC root zone was signed, with the SOA serial 2010071501.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Root trust anchors are available from IANA.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Underneath the root there is a large set of top-level domains that must be signed in order to achieve full DNSSEC deployment.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The List of Internet top-level domains provides details about which of the existing top-level domains have been signed and linked to the root.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In March 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced the DNSSEC Lookaside Validation registry.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV was intended to make DNSSEC easier to deploy in the absence of a root trust anchor.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] At the time it was imagined that a validator might have to maintain large numbers of trust anchors corresponding to signed subtrees of the DNS.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The purpose of DLV was to allow validators to offload the effort of managing a trust anchor repository to a trusted third party.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The DLV registry maintained a central list of trust anchors, instead of each validator repeating the work of maintaining its own list.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] To use DLV, a validator that supports it was needed, such as BIND or Unbound, configured with a trust anchor for a DLV zone.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This zone contained DLV records; these had exactly the same format as DS records, but instead of referring to a delegated sub-zone, they referred to a zone elsewhere in the DNS tree.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] When the validator could not find a chain of trust from the root to the RRset it is trying to check, it searched for a DLV record that could provide an alternative chain of trust.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Gaps in the chain of trust, such as unsigned top-level domains or registrars that did not support DNSSEC delegations, meant administrators of lower-level domains could use DLV to allow their DNS data to be validated by resolvers which had been configured to use DLV.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] This may have hindered DNSSEC deployment by taking pressure off registrars and TLD registries to properly support DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV also added complexity by adding more actors and code paths for DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] ISC decommissioned its DLV registry in 2017.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DLV support was deprecated in BIND 9.12 and completely removed from BIND 9.16.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Unbound version 1.5.4 (July 2015) marked DLV as decommissioned in the example configuration and manual page.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Knot Resolver and PowerDNS Recursor never implemented DLV.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In March 2020, the IETF published RFC 8749, retiring DLV as a standard and moving RFC 4432 and RFC 5074 to "Historic" status.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Science and Technology Directorate of the U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) sponsors the "DNSSEC Deployment Initiative".
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] It was reported that on March 30, 2007, the U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security proposed "to have the key to sign the DNS root zone solidly in the hands of the US government." However no U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Government officials were present in the meeting room and the comment that sparked the article was made by another party.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DHS later commented on why they believe others jumped to the false conclusion that the U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Government had made such a proposal: "The U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Department of Homeland Security is funding the development of a technical plan for implementing DNSSec, and last October distributed an initial draft of it to a long list of international experts for comments.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The draft lays out a series of options for who could be the holder, or "operator," of the Root Zone Key, essentially boiling down to a governmental agency or a contractor.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) published NIST Special Publication 800-81 Secure Domain Name System (DNS) Deployment Guide on May 16, 2006, with guidance on how to deploy DNSSEC.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NIST intended to release new DNSSEC Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) requirements in NIST SP800-53-R1, referencing this deployment guide.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] U.S. agencies would then have had one year after final publication of NIST SP800-53-R1 to meet these new FISMA requirements.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] However, at the time NSEC3 had not been completed.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] NIST had suggested using split domains, a technique that is known to be possible but is difficult to deploy correctly, and has the security weaknesses noted above.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] On 22 August 2008, the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) released a memorandum requiring U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Federal Agencies to deploy DNSSEC across .gov sites; the .gov root must be signed by January 2009, and all subdomains under .gov must be signed by December 2009.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] While the memo focuses on .gov sites, the U.S.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Defense Information Systems Agency says it intends to meet OMB DNSSEC requirements in the .mil (U.S. military) domain as well.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Several ISPs have started to deploy DNSSEC-validating DNS recursive resolvers.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Comcast became the first major ISP to do so in the United States, announcing their intentions on October 18, 2010 and completing deployment on January 11, 2012.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] According to a study at APNIC, the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation rose to 8.3% in May 2013.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] About half of these clients were using Google's public DNS resolver.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2015, Verisign announced their free public DNS resolver service, and although unmentioned in their press releases, it also performs DNSSEC validation.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] By the beginning of 2016, APNIC's monitoring showed the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation had increased to about 15%.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Google's public recursive DNS server enabled DNSSEC validation on May 6, 2013.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] BIND, the most popular DNS management software, enables DNSSEC support by default since version 9.5.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] The Quad9 public recursive DNS has performed DNSSEC validation on its main 9.9.9.9 address since it was established on May 11, 2016.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Quad9 also provides an alternate service which does not perform DNSSEC validation, principally for debugging.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In September 2023, Microsoft announced it would utilize DNSSEC (via DANE) to verify the authenticity of certificates during SMTP communications.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Geoff Huston has argued that DNSSEC deployment should be given up.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In 2016, email provider Fastmail published a blog post stating that the company does not plan on implementing DNSSEC, referencing the many DNSSEC-related outages that had occurred around the time.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] More positive reactions have been put forward by internet infrastructure corporation Cloudflare, which hired one of the founders of DNSSEC to help implement it at the company.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] Domain registry Spaceship (a brand owned by Namecheap) enables DNSSEC automatically for supported domains it hosts the nameservers of.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] In 2025, Dutch registry SIDN argued against the claim that DNSSEC is complex when compared to other internet protocols.
[src:dns-security/domain-name-system-security-extensions] DNSSEC deployment requires software on the server and client side.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] A zone transfer uses the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) for transport, and takes the form of a client–server transaction.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The client requesting a zone transfer may be a secondary server requesting data from a primary server.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The portion of the database that is replicated is a zone.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Zone transfer consists of a preamble, followed by the actual data transfer.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The preamble comprises a lookup of the Start of Authority (SOA) resource record for the "zone apex", the node of the DNS namespace that is at the top of the "zone".
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The fields of this SOA resource record, in particular the "serial number", determine whether the actual data transfer need to occur at all.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The client compares the serial number of the SOA resource record with the serial number in the last copy of that resource record that it has.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] If the serial number of the record being transferred is greater, the data in the zone are deemed to have "changed" (in some fashion) and the secondary proceeds to request the actual zone data transfer.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] If the serial numbers are identical, the data in the zone are deemed not to have "changed", and the client may continue to use the copy of the database that it already has, if it has one.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The actual data transfer process begins by the client sending a query (opcode 0) with the special query type AXFR (value 252) over the TCP connection to the server.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Although DNS technically supports AXFR over User Datagram Protocol (UDP), it is considered not acceptable due to the risk of lost, or spoofed packets.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The server responds with a series of response messages, comprising all of the resource records for every domain name in the "zone".
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The first response comprises the SOA resource record for the zone apex.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The other data follows in no specified order.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The end of the data is signaled by the server repeating the response containing the SOA resource record for the zone apex.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Some zone transfer clients perform the SOA lookup of the preamble using their system's normal DNS query resolution mechanism.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] These clients do not open a TCP connection to the server until they have determined that they need to perform the actual data transfer.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] However, since TCP can be used for normal DNS transactions, as well as for zone transfer, other zone transfer clients perform the SOA lookup preamble over the same TCP connection as they then (may) perform the actual data transfer.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] These clients open the TCP connection to the server before they even perform the preamble.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The preceding describes full zone transfer.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Zone transfer is entirely client-initiated.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Though servers can send a NOTIFY message to clients (that they have been informed about) whenever a change to the zone data has been made, the scheduling of zone transfers is entirely under the control of the clients.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Clients schedule zone transfers initially, when their databases are empty, and thereafter at regular intervals, in a pattern controlled by the values in the "refresh", "retry", and "expire" fields in the SOA resource record of the zone apex.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Though it is standardized, full-zone transfer being described as one of the possible database replication mechanisms in RFC 1034 and RFC 5936 (incremental zone transfer described in RFC 1995), zone transfer is the most limited of those database replication mechanisms.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Zone transfer operates in terms of "wire format" resource records, *i.e.* resource records as they are transferred using the DNS protocol.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] However, the schema of wire format resource records may not be identical to the database schema used by the back ends of the DNS servers themselves.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The preamble portion of zone transfer relies on the serial number, and *only* the serial number, to determine whether a zone's data have changed, and thus whether the actual data transfer is required.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] For some DNS server packages, the serial numbers of SOA resource records are maintained by administrators by hand.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Every edit to the database involves making two changes, one to the record being changed and the other to the zone serial number.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The process requires accuracy: the administrator may forget to change the serial number or change it incorrectly (reduce it).
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] RFC 1912 (section 2.2 SOA records) recommends using the value YYYYMMDDnn as the number (YYYY=year, MM=month, DD=day, nn=revision number).
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] This won't overflow until the year 4294.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Some DNS server packages have overcome this problem by automatically constructing the serial number from the last modification timestamp of the database file on disk.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] This is the case for djbdns, for example.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The operating system ensures that the last modification timestamp is updated whenever an administrator edits the database file, effectively automatically updating the serial number, and thus relieving administrators of the need to make two edits (in two different places) for every single change.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] This paradigm simply does not match that of a single, central, monotonically increasing number to record changes, and thus is incompatible with zone transfer to a large extent.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Modern DNS server packages with sophisticated database back ends often will create a "shim" serial number, simulating the existence of a single central place where updates are made, but this is at best imperfect.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Serial number comparisons are intended to use Serial Number Arithmetic as defined in RFC 1982.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] However, this was not clearly specified in RFC 1034, resulting in not all clients perform the serial number check, in the preamble, in the same way.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Some clients check merely that the serial number supplied by the server is different from that known by the client, or non-zero.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Other clients check that the serial number supplied by the server is within a given range of the serial number already known by the client.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Yet other clients still perform the latter check and additionally check that the serial number supplied by the server is not zero.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Originally, in the actual data transfer each set of resource records for a single domain name and type was transferred in a separate response message from the server to the client.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Some clients were written to expect *only* the original response format, and would fail to perform data transfer if such optimizations were employed.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] Several DNS server packages thus have a configuration setting allowing administrators to specify the use of "single answer format" responses for those clients that require it.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] The data contained in a DNS zone may be sensitive from an operational security aspect.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] This is because information such as server hostnames may become public knowledge, which can be used to discover information about an organization and even provide a larger attack surface.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] In June 2017 the registrar responsible for Russian top-level-domains accidentally enabled DNS zone transfers via AXFR which led to 5.6 million records being accidentally exposed.
[src:dns-security/zone-transfer] In 2008 a court in North Dakota, USA, ruled that performing a zone transfer as an unauthorized outsider to obtain information that was not publicly accessible constitutes a violation of North Dakota law.
